details.purpose: To record detailed findings about a non-neoplastic renal biopsy
details.use: To record detailed findings about microscopic examination of tissue related to glomerular, tubulointerstitial and vascular renal diseases. Use as a component archetype in the context of a suite of archetypes that make up a histopathology report i.e. OBSERVATION.lab_test.histopathology
details.misuse: Not designed to be used within any other archetype other than OBSERVATION.lab_test.histopathology.

items.items: Microscopic findings related to a non-neoplastic renal biopsy
Describes tissue types in the renal biopsy specimen.
Cortical tissue present, alternatively core length with cortical tissue, alternatively proportion of cortical tissue in relation to the core with renal tissue.
Presence of cortical tissue has not been determined.
Medullary tissue present, alternatively core length with medullary tissue, alternatively proportion of medullary tissue in relation to the core with renal tissue.
Presence of medullary tissue has not been determined.
A statement whether the renal capsule is present.
Description of other tissue elements, e.g. muscle tissue.
Sceletal muscle and/or fat tissue and/or connective tissue
Sceletal muscle and/or fat tissue and/or connective tissue present.
The maximum number of glomeruli irrespective of size present in one section; structures consisting of Bowman's capsule with empty Bowman's space are excluded.
The number of glomeruli judged as adequate for scoring by the reporting pathologist.
The number of glomeruli showing fibrinoid necrosis without crescent formation.
The number of glomeruli showing cellular or fibrocellular crescents.
The number of glomeruli showing some degree of tuft retraction and wrinkling of capillary walls. Chronic ischemic changes might show fibrosis of Bowman's capsule.
The number of glomeruli showing obliteration of capillary lumen by extracellular matrix in a portion of the tuft area with or without adhesions to the Bowman capsule, hyaline lesions, foam cells.
The number of glomeruli showing scarring with obliteration of capillary lumen by extracellular matrix in the entire or nearly entire glomerular tuft.
The number of glomeruli which appear normal without major changes.

A narrative description of glomerular findings, e.g. mesangial and endocapillary cellularity, capillary wall changes, podocytes, Bowman's space. For structured description of specific renal diseases use appropriate cluster (IgA nephropathy, lupus nephritis).
Slot for detailed description of specific glomerular changes. Include: openEHR-EHR-CLUSTER.glomerulus_segmental_glomerulosclerosis_classification.v1.
Structured report of kind of tubular casts present.
Characteristic myeloma casts, often surrounded by reactive tubular epithelial cells. or multinucleated cells, present in tubular lumen.
Presence of intratubular Tamm Horsfall protein.
Presence of hyalin casts in tubular lumen.
Presence of granular casts in tubular lumen.
Detached cells, commonly epithelial cells, present in the tubular lumen.
Collections of red blood cells or red blood cell casts present in tubular lumen.
Presence of neutrophil granulocytes in tubular lumen.
Semiquantitative or quantitative assessment of tubular atrophy.
Semiquantitative visual assessment of tubular atrophy.
Tubular atrophy is not present or minimal (few transsections).
Tubular atrophy in up to 25 % of the area of cortical tubules.
Tubular atrophy involving 25 - 50% of the area of cortical tubules.
Tubular atrophy present in more than 50% of the area of cortical tubules.
Tubular atrophy could not be assessed, e.g. due to bad sections.
Desription of tubular changes, e.g. hyalin droplet change, acute epithelial damage, cytoplasmic vacuolation, sloughing of cells, loss of brush border.
Interstitial changes, especially semiquantitative or quantitative assessment of interstitial fibrosis.
Quantification of interstitial fibrosis by image analysis methods.
To record details of the image analysis, e.g. software, algorithm.
Sirius red stain unpolarized used for fibrosis quantification by image analysis
Sirius red stain polarized used for fibrosis quantification by image analysis
Collagen III immunohistochemical stain used for fibrosis quantification by image analysis
Percentage of the renal cortical tissue involved by fibrosis.
Visual quantification of interstitial fibrosis; The fibrosis percentage is the percentage of abnormal cortical tissue with fibrosis.
Visual quantification of interstitial fibrosis; The fibrosis percentage is the percentage of all cortical tissue (excluding tubules and glomeruli) occupied by fibrous tissue.
Description of interstitial changes, e.g. edema, inflammatory cells, deposits.
Changes affecting arteries, arterioles, venes and peritubular capillaries.
Number of arteries in a renal biopsy.
Amount of arteriosclerosis in the most affected vessel.
There is no intimal sclerosis or intimal sclerosis is minimal.
There is < 25% lumen narrowing by intimal fibrosis.
There is 25% - 50% lumen narrowing by intimal fibrosis.
There is > 50% lumen narrowing by intimal fibrosis.
Amount of arteriolosclerosis in the most affected vessel.
Description of vascular changes, e.g. vasculitis, venulitis. For description of severity of arteriosclerosis and arteriolosclerosis use coded text.
Slot for detailed description of specific glomerular changes. Include: openEHR-EHR-CLUSTER.amyloid_deposition.v1
Detailed structured description for specific clinical situations, e.g. biopsy of renal transplant, lupus nephritis, IgA nephropathy.
Images from lesions could be attached here.
Images, graphs and tables from automatic image analysis of interstitial fibrosis.
Choose the type of casts present in tubuli. Multiple choices possible.
Casts consisting of more than one component.
Discolorated casts e.g. due to hemoglobin, myoglobin, drug pigments, bilirubin, melanin.
Enlarged podocytes often with amphophil cytoplasm.
Bi- or multinucleated podocytes are not seen.
Bi- or multinucleated podocytes are seen.
Presence of bi- or mulitnucleated podocytes has not been determined.
Presence of bi- or mulitnucleated podocytes is equivocal.
Podocytes with PAS positive resorption droplets.
Podocytes with resorption droplets are not present.
One or few podocytes with resorption droplets are present.
Numerous podocytes with resorption droplets are present.
Presence of podocytes with resorption droplets could not be assessed, e.g. due tof bad morphology.
It is uncertain whether podocytes with resorption droplets are present or not.
Podocytes with resorption droplets are not present.
One of few podocytes with resorption droplets are present.
Numerous podocytes with resorption droplets are present.
It is uncertain whether podocytes with resorption droplets are present or not.
Presence of podocytes with resorption droplets could not be assessed, e.g. due to bad morphology.
It is uncertain whether podocyte size is normal or enlarged.
Podocyte size could not be assessed, e.g. due to bad morphology.
Statement that no abnormality was detected on examination of the mesangial areas.
Statement that no abnormality was detected on examination of podocytes.
A narrative description of mesangial changes.
Visual assessment of the amount of mesangial matrix.
It is uncertain, whether mesangial matrix is increased.
A narrative description of podocyte changes.
Mesangial matrix increase could not be assessed. e.g. due to bad morphology.

A visual assessment of the cellularity of the mesangium. Normally there are 1 - 3 cells per mesangial area. The score is based on the most cellular mesangial area. Mesangial areas adjacent to the vascular stalk should not be scored.
Definitions based on Roberts et al, 2009.
There is no increase in mesangial cells.
There is a slight increase in mesangial cellularity, usually 4-5 cells per mesangial area.
There is a moderate increase in mesangial cellularity, usually 6-7 cells per mesangial area.
There is a severe increase in mesangial cellularity, usually 8 or more cells per mesangial area.
It is uncertain whether there is an increase in mesangial cellularity or not.
Mesangial cellularity could not be assessed, e.g. due to bad morphology or thick sections.
Statement that no abnormality was detected on examination of the glomerular capillaries.
A visual assessment of the capillary wall thickness.
A narrative description of glomerular capillary changes.
Glomerular capillary walls are not thickened.
Glomerular capillary walls are focally thickened.
Glomerular capillary walls are diffusely thickened.
Glomerular capillary walls are segmentally thickened.
Glomerular capillary walls are globally thickened.
It is uncertain whether glomerular capillary walls are thickened.
Glomerular capillary wall thickness could not be assessed, e.g. due to section thickness.
A visual assessment of the presence of capillary wall duplication.
Capillary wall duplication is not present.
Capillary wall duplication is focally present.
Capillary wall duplication is diffusely present.
Capillary wall duplication is segmentally present.
Capillary wall duplication is globally present.
It is unceratin whether capillary wall duplication is present.
Capillary wall thickening could not be assessed, e.g. due to bad morphology.
Description of changes in the capillary lumens.
It is uncertain whether there is endocapillary hypercellularity.
Endocapillary cellularity could not be assessed, e.g. due to bad morphology.
Endothelial cells are part of the intracapillary infiltrate.
Macrophages are part of the intracapillary infiltrate.
Neutrophil granulocytes are part of the intracapillary infiltrate.
Lymphocytes are part of the intracapillary infiltrate.
Atypical cells are part of the intracapillary infiltrate.
Intracapillary thrombi are present in less than half of the glomeruli.
Intracapillary thrombi are present in more than half of the glomeruli.
Intracapillary thrombi are present only in a part of the glomerular tuft.
Intracapillary thrombi are present in the whole glomerular tuft.
It is uncertain whether intracapillary thrombi are present or not.
Presence of intracapillary thrombi could not be assessed, e.g. because of bad sections.
The intracapillary thrombi are mainly hyalinous.
The intracapillary thrombi consist mainly of fibrin.
A visual assesment of the presence of interposed cells in the capillary periphery.
It is uncertain whether mesangial interposition is present.
Mesangial interposition could not be assessed, e.g. because of bad sections.
A visual assessment of the presence of acellular PAS positive mesangial nodules.
It is uncertain whether mesangial nodules are present.
Presence of mesangial nodules could not be assessed, e.g. because of bad sections.
Description of tubular epithelial cell changes. Multiple choices possible.
PAS positive absorption droplets in the epithelium of proximal tubules, usually indicating glomerular proteinuria.

Fine, even vacuolization of the proximal tubular epithelium. Hydropic change is a synonym. If related to infusion of hypertonic solutions, the change is also described as osmotic nephrosis. If related to cyclosporin therapy, the change is called isometric vacuolization.
Irregular and coarse vacuolization of the tubular epithelium. The change might be associated with hypokaliemia or tubulotoxicity.
Fine vacuoles containing lipid, often at the base of the tubular epithelial cells. Fat can be demonstrated by lipid stains on frozen sections.
Enlarged mitochondria visuable as eosinophilic bodies in tubular epithelial cells.
The number of glomeruli showing coneective tissue connections between the tuft and Bowman's capsule without overt sclerosis.
A statement that no abnormality was detected in renal tubules.
A statement that no abnormality was detected in the renal interstitium.
A statement that no abnormality was detected in the renal vasculature.
A statement that no amyloid deposition was detected.
